Introduction


The aim of this paper is to analyze the excess returns of ARMOUR Residential REIT, Inc.(ARR ticker), in the period January 2016-December 2020, using the R software.
In particular, the focus of this research is to display how to use the R code to perform a correct analysis of the returns.
The company chosen is a small cap, value firm. The market capitalization is equal to 872.536M and the P/E ratio equals 5.44.

In the first part it is explained how to import the dataset and how to perform a descriptive analysis of the data, an ARIMA model is fitted.
In the second part the Single-Index model and the Fama-French Three-Factor model are fitted into the data with the OLS regression approach and a diagnostic of the residuals is performed at the end.
We want to establish if the Fama-French model can capture the extra-market risk exposure of the company and can explain better than the single-index model the firms excess returns variability.

The single-index model implies a regression of ARMOURs excess returns on the market excesss returns, while the Fama-French model implies a regression of ARMOURs excess returns on the market excess returns and on the SMB and HML proxies.

Lets look at the relevant variables that are going to be used inside this paper:
- R_ARR: the ARMOUR REITs excess returns (simple returns - risk free rate = excess returns);
- R_MKT: the market excess returns. Given that its impossible to observe the true market portfolio, a proxy is used instead;
- SMB (Small-Minus-Big): this is a proxy for some extra-market risk factors that are difficult to be observed. In particular, its the return of a portfolio of small stocks in excess of the return on a portfolio of large stocks (Bodie, Kane, Marcus - Investments);
- HML (High-Minus-Low): another extra-market risk proxy. In this case its the return of a portfolio of stocks with a high book-to-market ratio in excess of the return on a portfolio of stocks with a low book-to-market ratio (Bodie, Kane, Marcus - Investments).
The analyzed period is January 2016 December 2020 and all the data are monthly.

A detailed description of how the variables R_MKT, HML and SMB are built can be found directly in the Kenneth French Data Library https://mba.tuck.dartmouth.edu/pages/faculty/ken.french/data_library.html, where they are downloaded.
R_ARR, ARMOURs excess returns, are computed in an excel spreadsheet from prices downloaded in the yahoo finance website. It will be presented how to compute the returns from prices with R too.

Data retreiving and cleaning


The data is inside two external documents that are called F-F.csv and ARR.xlsx.
The first one is a comma-separated values (.csv) file in which the variables R_MKT, SMB and HML are stored. It is downloaded directly from the Professor Kenneth French data library.
The second one is a Microsoft Excel file (.xlsx) which includes the company stock price, the simple returns and the excess returns. We are interested only in the excess returns (R_ARR).

The function read.table is useful to import data from .csv documents.
The dataset to be imported in R must be in your active working directory.

riskfactors <- read.table('F-F.csv', sep=',', dec='.', header=TRUE,
                                         row.names = 1, encoding='UTF-8',
                                                 na.strings='')

Type ?read.table in the console to access the help page of the function and the complete argument descriptions.
In this case the field separator is the comma and the decimal separator is the dot.
The missing values are coded with blank spaces (na.strings), the first row is a header (a row with variable names) and the first column includes row names.
The encoding is specified too (encoding=UTF-8).


The function read_excel can be used to import the excel spreadsheet. The reference package is readxl.

returns <- read_excel('ARR.xlsx', col_types=c('date', 
                                rep('numeric', times=5)), 
                                         col_names=TRUE, na='')

The missing values are coded again with blank spaces (na= ) and even if the column type is guessed by default but its better specify it. In this case the first column contains dates, the other five numerical variables.
The col_names argument equals the header argument of the read.table function.

The window function allows instead to assign the dataframe variables to single objects.

R_ARR <- window(returns$`ARRexcessRet(perc)`) 
R_MKT <- window(riskfactors$Mkt.RF) 
SMB <- window(riskfactors$SMB) 
HML <- window(riskfactors$HML) 
date <- window(returns$Date)

We assigned a specific object for each of the variables of interest plus an object with the dates, that will be useful later.


The objects just created are numerical vectors but its better to work with time series when analyzing returns or prices.
When there is the necessity to convert a numerical vector into a time series object, two different paths can be followed: to use the ts function from the basic package stats or to use the xts function, from the xts package. The latter produces an object of class zoo (look at the zoo package) while the first produces a basic ts class object.
Now we are converting our numerical vectors in ts class objects, later we will deal with zoo class objects and the xts function.

R_ARR <- ts(R_ARR, start=c(2015, 12), end=c(2021, 1), frequency = 12) 
R_MKT <- ts(R_MKT, start=c(2015, 12), end=c(2021, 1), frequency = 12) 
SMB <- ts(SMB, start=c(2015, 12), end=c(2021, 1), frequency = 12) 
HML <- ts(HML, start=c(2015, 12), end=c(2021, 1), frequency = 12)

As it is displayed, the ts function requires that the time interval of the observations is specified.

mode(R_ARR)
class(R_ARR)
## [1] "numeric"
## [1] "ts"

The R_ARR object is still numeric in mode, but the class is ts, time-series now.


The code below is useful to find how much missing values there are in each series.

In this case, given that the number of observations is low, you can type in the console the name of each variable and find where the NA is located. Each variable has a NA in Dec 2015.


The function getSymbols from the quantmod package allows to download directly in R the data from the internet and to assign it to an R object (automatically or not, it depends on the auto.assign argument value). The code below illustrates how to download the adjusted closing prices of ARMOUR from yahoo finance. Then, the excess returns are computed.

data.quant<- getSymbols(Symbols='ARR', src='yahoo', 
                        verbose=T, auto.assign = F) # daily data
data.quant<- to.monthly(data.quant) # monthly data
p.ARR.quant <- window(data.quant$data.quant.Adjusted) # adjusted 
# monthly closing prices

p.ARR.quant <- p.ARR.quant['2015-12/2021-01'] # select only the analyzed period
# Dec 2015 - Jan 2021

R.ARR.quant <- ROC(p.ARR.quant, type='discrete')*100 # simple returns

RF.rate <- window(returns$`RF(perc)`)
RF.rate <- xts(RF.rate, order.by=date, frequency=12) # rf rate as xts obj

R.ARR.quant <- R.ARR.quant - RF.rate 
colnames(R.ARR.quant) <- 'ARRexcRet' 
# ARR excess returns from Dec 2015 to Jan 2021

The ticker of ARMOUR is ARR and must be specified inside getSymbols. The function downloads daily price observations (open, close, adj close, volume, high, low).
We need monthly data and then the to.monthly function is useful here.
Consider that the data downloaded includes different variables, but we need only the adjusted monthly closing prices. Once an object with monthly adjusted closing prices is obtained (p.ARR.quant) it must be subsetted according to the analysis period.
Then, with the ROC function, simple returns can be easily computed and once the risk free rate is subtracted the excess returns are obtained (R.ARR.quant object).

mode(R.ARR.quant)
class(R.ARR.quant)
## [1] "numeric"
## [1] "xts" "zoo"

R.ARR.quant is an object of numeric mode and zoo (xts) class. When stock prices are downloaded with getSymbols, a zoo class object is returned automatically.


Descriptive analysis


We will use the objects imported from external datasets: R_ARR (ARMOURs excess returns), R_MKT (market excess returns), SMB and HML.

Lets start coding a plot which depicts the ARMOURs excess returns and the market excess returns.

ts.plot(R_ARR, R_MKT, col=c('red', 'blue'), lty=c(1,1), lwd=c(2,2), 
                                   main='ARMOUR vs Market excess returns',
                        xlab='Years', ylab='% Monthly Excess Returns')

legend('bottomleft', legend=c('ARMOUR', 'Market'), lty = c(1,1), 
            cex=c(1.2), col=c('red', 'blue'), text.col=c('red', 'blue'))

ts.plot and legend are two R base functions. The first one is a high level plotting function which creates a new plot, the second one is a low level plotting function which modifies the plot just created, in this case adding a legend.
We will see later other examples of high level and low level plotting functions, and we will see that there is a package of the Tidyverse, ggplot2, which allows to procuce plots whith a different code syntax based on layers.

An important thing to remember here is to respect the order of the variables inside the code: if R_ARR is the first variable to be plotted, then all the arguments must specify for first the characteristics of the R_ARR plot. If you want it to be red, then red must be the first color inside col=c(red, blue) and so on.
Note that you can tune the dimension of the legend with cex.

From this plot it can be observed that ARMOURs returns are far more volatile than the market, as can be expected. In particular there is a volatility cluster in the first semester of 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic outbreak. A whopping negative peak of -50.97 is registered in March 2020, followed by increasing returns in the following months.


summary(R_ARR)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max.     NA's 
## -50.9759  -2.3788   1.5602   0.2589   4.4326  19.9134        1
summary(R_MKT)

The summary function can be very useful to evaluate numerical objects like these. It provides different statistics, including the number of NAs (only 1 in ths case).
Summary is a generic R function: this means that the output depends on the object type. Before, summary has been used to check quickly the structure of a dataframe class object, and the output was different.

The mean excess return in the analyzed period is 0.2589 for ARMOUR while the same statistic takes a value of 1.267 for the market instead, a far greater value. Its clear and not surprising that the COVID-19 pandemic has had a stronger impact on ARMOURs returns with respect to the market portfolio.


Autocorrelation structure

Its important to understand the autocorrelation structure of the time series used in the analysis. The functions acf and pacf are useful for this purpose: the first one computes the autocorrelation function and the second one the partial ACF.

par(mfrow=(c(2,2)))
acf(R_ARR, na.action=na.pass, main='ACF of ARMOUR excess returns')
acf(R_MKT, na.action=na.pass, main='ACF of market excess returns')
pacf(R_ARR, na.action=na.pass, main= 'PACF of ARMOUR excess returns')
pacf(R_MKT, na.action=na.pass, main='PACF of market excess returns')

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

To display the ACF and the PACF of R_ARR and R_MKT in the same plot its necessary to divide the figure region in four parts and to assign to each part one plot. This can be done with par(mfrow=c(2,2)): it divides the figure region in a 2x2 matrix.
par(mfrow=c(1,1)) its needed to reset the figure region.
na.pass is an argument needed to deal with missing values (NAs).

Both series, market excess returns and ARMOURs excess returns, are not autocorrelated or partially autocorrelated.

Arima fitting

An ARIMA model can be fitted into R_ARR (ARMOURs excess returns) and into R_MKT (excess returns of the market). Given that both series are stationary and not autocorrelted, its expected a white noise like behavior from them.
The auto.arima function from the package forecast can be used to automatically fit an ARIMA class model into the data, according to an information criterion.

arima_fit_ARR <- auto.arima(R_ARR)
arima_fit_MKT <- auto.arima(R_MKT)

To see the results, use summary.

Remember always to check the residuals after estimating any model.

Both models fit the data well.




Regression analysis: Single-Index and Fama-French models


There are four assumptions behind the OLS regression to be checked:
1. Linear relationship between the regressand and each of the regressors
2. Independence of the residuals (check if they are autocorrelated)
3. Homoskedasticity of the residuals
4. Normality of the residuals

A good starting point is to check the normality of the regressand, R_ARR (ARMOURs excess returns). Then, we will check graphically the linear relationship between the regressand and each of the regressors.


Check the normality of R_ARR series


A histogram helps to understand the probability density shape of the distribution.

hist(R_ARR, breaks=50, main='Histogram of ARMOUR Residential returns',
                            xlab='', border='red', density=TRUE, 
                        freq=FALSE, las=1)
text(x=-16, y=9, 'The returns display fat tails', cex=1)
box(col='blue')

hist is a high level plotting function, text and box are low level plotting functions. text allows to add some text inside the plot at the specified coordinates, box allows to tune the plot border color.
The argument breaks tunes the numbers of cells of the histogram, while the argument freq must be equal to FALSE to get probability densities.

Its clear that the ARMOURs excess returns display fat tails.


The Adjusted JarqueBera test for normality can be run too.

ajb.norm.test(R_ARR[!is.na(R_ARR)])
## 
##  Adjusted Jarque-Bera test for normality
## 
## data:  R_ARR[!is.na(R_ARR)]
## AJB = 956.37, p-value < 2.2e-16

The test rejects H0 (the normality assumption) at alpha = 0.05.
Note that R_ARR must be subsetted in order to delete missing values from the series.

Finally you may want to understand in which way the series deviates from the normality assumption: a qqplot can be a useful tool to do this.

qqnorm(R_ARR, pch=20, cex=1.2, col='tomato', axes=F,
                                   xlab='Theoretical quantiles', 
                                  ylab='Sample quantiles')
axis(1, pos=-55, col='black', lty=2)
axis(2, pos=-2.5, las=T, col='black', lty=2)
qqline(R_ARR, col = 'navy')
legend(-2, 20, legend=c('Sample quantiles', 'Reference line'), 
        pch=c(20, NA), lty=c(NA, 1), cex=c(1, 1),
                     col=c('tomato', 'navy'), text.col=c('black', 'black'))

The qqplot shows that the tails are fatter than the normal assumption, a characteristic that we observed in the histogram too.
In this case qqnorm is a high level plotting function, while axis, qqline and legend are low level plottig functions.
Note that this plot has custom axes: set axes=F inside qqnorm and then add your custom axes with axis.
pch and cex allow to set the plotted symbol and its scale, respectively.
With legend you can set almost every aspect of your legend, but you have to respect the order of the variables to get a correct result.

To proceed, the normality of R_ARR (ARMOURs excess returns) must be assumed. Pay attention when you are assuming normality though, it may lead to dramatically wrong results, in particular when you are dealing with risk management.


Create a new dataframe with all the useful data


Before continuing its better to organize the data in a unique dataframe, more specifically an object of class zoo (xts). At the same moment, the observations of Dec 2015 are removed because they are only missing values (NAs). The observations of Jan 2021 are removed too. Then, the new dataframe contains only observations for the period Jan 2016 - Dec 2020.

all.dataframe <- data.frame(R_ARR, R_MKT, SMB, HML)
all.dataframe <- xts(all.dataframe, order.by = date, frequency = 12)
all.dataframe <- all.dataframe['2016-01-01/2020-12-01']

There are three passages to get this job done (look at the code above):
1. Create an object of class data.frame with the data.frame function;
2. Convert the data.frame class object into a zoo class object with the function xts. You have to specify a vector of dates (with order.by), thats an object of class POSIXct, POSIXt;
3. Subset the object according to the desired period.

In this way you obtain a dataframe with all the relevant variables of the regressions (R_ARR, R_MKT, SMB, HML) in a format thats useful for the analysis (its a zoo class object).

A confirm that NAs are deleted can be found with this chunk:

apply(all.dataframe, MARGIN = 2, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
## R_ARR R_MKT   SMB   HML 
##     0     0     0     0

The apply function applies a function to the margins of a matrix. It can work with a dataframe like all.dataframe too.
MARGIN=2 means that you want to apply the function to the columns of the dataframe. The function applied is function(x) sum(is.na(x)).
The output describes the number of NAs of each column (variable): all variables have zero NAs.


Check the linear relationship between the regressand (R_ARR) and each of the regressors (R_MKT, SMB, HML) of the models fitted


lindep1 <- ggplot(data=all.dataframe, mapping=aes(x=R_MKT, y=R_ARR)) +
              geom_point(size=4, shape=20, col='blue4', alpha=0.7)+
    ggtitle('ARMOUR vs Market excess returns')+
                         xlab('Market') + ylab('ARMOUR')+
                                           theme_stata()

lindep2 <- ggplot(data=all.dataframe, mapping=aes(x=SMB, y=R_ARR)) +
  geom_point(size=4, shape=20, col='red', alpha=0.7)+
  ggtitle('ARMOUR excess returns vs SMB')+
  xlab('SMB') + ylab('ARMOUR')+
  theme_stata()

lindep3 <- ggplot(data=all.dataframe, mapping=aes(x=HML, y=R_ARR)) +
  geom_point(size=4, shape=20, col='grey4', alpha=0.7)+
  ggtitle('ARMOUR excess returns vs HML')+
  xlab('HML') + ylab('ARMOUR')+
  theme_stata()

grid.arrange(lindep1, lindep2, lindep3, ncol=2)

The code displayed above produces a plot with four figure regions, but only three of them include a plot. The function used to get a plot like this is grid.arrange and you have to name all the plot objects to be arranged.

The package used here is ggplot2 from the tidverse.
Basically, this package allows to build plots with a code syntax based on layers.
You have to initialize the graphical page with the ggplot function and then add the plot components inside each layer of code. For example, the geom_point function allows to plot the variables specified in ggplot as points producing a scatterplot.

The linear relationship is assumed between R_ARR (the regressand, ARMOURs excess returns) and each of the regressors (R_MKT -market excess returns-, HML and SMB), on the basis of the graphical evidence.


OLS approach - Single-index and Fama-French models regression


The Single-Index model implies the regression of ARMOURs excess returns (R_ARR) on the market excess returns (R_MKT). The regression coefficient found is called beta and the intercept is called alpha.
Alpha is the abnormal stocks return while beta is the stocks responsiveness to the market return.
The function lm of the R package stats allows to fit any linear model, while summary returns the output.

s.i.OLS <- lm(R_ARR~R_MKT, data=all.dataframe)
summary(s.i.OLS)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = R_ARR ~ R_MKT, data = all.dataframe)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -35.824  -2.866   0.771   4.283  18.499 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  -1.1585     1.0167  -1.139    0.259    
## R_MKT         1.0458     0.2107   4.964  6.4e-06 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 7.59 on 58 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2982, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2861 
## F-statistic: 24.64 on 1 and 58 DF,  p-value: 6.404e-06

The intercept (alpha) isnt significant, while the beta is significant and equal to 1.0458 (considering the period Jan 2016-Dec 2020). The R-squared equals 0.2982.
The level of beta found is almost equal to the beta of the market (1 by construction). This means that ARMOURs stock should follow closely the market portfolio movements.


The Fama-French Three-Factor model is a step forward with respect to the Single-Index model. It adds two more regressors: SMB and HML. These variables, as explained in the introducion paragraph, proxy for the extra-market risk exposure of the stock, difficult to observe. SMB and HML are included in the F-F model because, on empirical ground, they seem to proxy for exposure to systematic (non-diversifiable) risk.
If the regression coefficients (beta) of HML and SMB are found significant, the risk factors behind these proxies have influenced past returns.
The sensitivity to changes of the proxied risk factors is again represented by the correspondent beta coefficient. If the beta of SMB is found significant and positive, for example, some non-diversifiable (systematic) extra-market risk exposure, linked with the small capitalization of the firm, is detected. On the other hand, a high HML beta signals a risk exposure linked with the small P/E ratio of the (value) company.

The linear model is fitted with lm:

FF.OLS <- lm(R_ARR~R_MKT+SMB+HML, data=all.dataframe)
summary(FF.OLS)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = R_ARR ~ R_MKT + SMB + HML, data = all.dataframe)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -26.5493  -3.4478   0.5473   3.3075  18.9864 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  -0.2972     0.9963  -0.298 0.766591    
## R_MKT         0.8066     0.2235   3.610 0.000655 ***
## SMB           0.4175     0.4060   1.028 0.308232    
## HML           0.8049     0.2934   2.743 0.008160 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 7.127 on 56 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.4024, Adjusted R-squared:  0.3704 
## F-statistic: 12.57 on 3 and 56 DF,  p-value: 2.156e-06

The intercept and SMB coefficient arent significant.
The market beta and the HML beta are significant, positive and equal to 0.80.
The R-squared is improved from 0.2982 to 0.4024.
Some extra-market risk exposure, linked with the fact that the firm is a value company with a low P/E ratio, is detected and this has improved the regression results with respect to the Single-Index model.


Regression function and looping


You may want to perform the regression analysis focusing only on a specified year: one way to do this is to build a function which fit the regression model only to the data belonging to the year selected.

I need a dataframe with all the data to fit the Fama-French model plus a variable column with only the year of each observation.

data.function<- data.frame(R_ARR, R_MKT, SMB, HML)
year <- format(date, format='%Y')
data.function <- data.function %>% add_column(year)
data.function <- data.function %>% filter(year > 2015 & year<2021)

format extracts a vector with only the year values from the vector with the dates (date). This year vector is added to a dataframe which includes all the data needed to perform the regression analysis of the Fama-French model.
The package tibble is used to manage the dataframes here. The pipe operator %>% is a characteristic of the tidyverse code syntax.


The chunk of code below is an example of such a regression function.
It fits the Fama-French model but it can be simplified to fit the Single-Index model too.
You have to specify only the year as argument.

reg.function <- function(reg.Year) {
  
  reg.model = lm(R_ARR ~., data = data.function %>% filter(year == reg.Year) 
                                                            %>% select(-year))
 
   return( data.frame ( year=reg.Year, 
             RSquared = summary(reg.model)$r.squared,
              Beta_mkt = summary(reg.model)$coefficients[2,1],
          Beta_SMB = summary(reg.model)$coefficients[3,1],
        Beta_HML = summary(reg.model)$coefficients[4,1]     )  )
                                                                     }

This function returns a dataframe with the year, the R squared and all the betas.
The dplyr package from the tydiverse (specifically the filter function) is used to subset the dataframe according to the year selected for the regression. select(-year) is needed to avoid to use the year column as a regressor.

reg.function(2016)
##   year  RSquared Beta_mkt   Beta_SMB   Beta_HML
## 1 2016 0.4327383 1.485001 -0.5118867 -0.3128154


If you want to run the Fama-French model regression to every year and store the results in a dataframe, you can use the regression function in loop. The purrr package from the Tidyverse can do the job.

reg.dataframe.short <- purrr::map_dfr(
                      .x = unique(data.function$year),
                          .f=reg.function)

The function map from the purrr package allows to apply a specified function to each element of a list or atomic vector.
You have to specify the mapping according to which the function is applied. In this case the mapping is given by unique(data.function$year), which returns 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020. This means that you want to apply the regression function to the data year by year.

The result is the following:

reg.dataframe.short
##   year  RSquared  Beta_mkt   Beta_SMB   Beta_HML
## 1 2016 0.4327383 1.4850013 -0.5118867 -0.3128154
## 2 2017 0.2193311 0.7431213  0.4308432 -1.3488465
## 3 2018 0.5440170 0.2765407  1.3974820  1.5970141
## 4 2019 0.6835033 0.8519283  0.1386388  0.4295855
## 5 2020 0.6341564 0.6719036 -0.8479346  2.7591451


Diagnostic of the regression residuals (Single-Index and Fama-French models)


Define the residuals time series for first:

res_s.i <- window(s.i.OLS$residuals) # single index model residuals
res_FF <- window(FF.OLS$residuals) # FF three factor model residuals

res_s.i <- ts(res_s.i, start=c(2016, 1), end=c(2020, 12), frequency = 12)
res_FF <- ts(res_FF, start=c(2016, 1), end=c(2020, 12), frequency = 12)


Normality of the residuals

Are the residuals of the two regressions (Single-Index and Fama-French) normally distributed?

Adjusted Jarque-Bera test for normality:

ajb.norm.test(res_s.i)
ajb.norm.test(res_FF)
## 
##  Adjusted Jarque-Bera test for normality
## 
## data:  res_s.i
## AJB = 217, p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
## 
##  Adjusted Jarque-Bera test for normality
## 
## data:  res_FF
## AJB = 35.605, p-value = 0.001

The test rejects for both assuming an alpha level (significance test) of 0.05. The residuals of the two models arent normally distributed.

A qq-plot will reveal the nature of the deviation from normality. Here is computed only the qq-plot for the Fama-French residuals.

qqnorm(res_FF, pch=20, cex=1.2, col='tomato', axes=F,
       xlab='Theoretical quantiles', 
       ylab='Sample quantiles')
axis(1, pos=-28, col='black', lty=2)
axis(2, pos=-2.6, col='black', lty=2, las=T)
qqline(res_FF, col = 'navy')
legend(1, -13, legend=c('Sample quantiles', 'Reference line'), 
       pch=c(20, NA), lty=c(NA, 1), cex=1.2,
       col=c('tomato', 'navy') , text.col = c('black', 'black'))

Analyzing the qq-plot its clear that fat tails are still persistent.


Homoskedasticity of the residuals

Breush-Pagan test for heteroskedasticity (H0:homoskedasticity, alpha level = 0.05).

bptest(s.i.OLS)
bptest(FF.OLS)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  s.i.OLS
## BP = 6.6514, df = 1, p-value = 0.009908
## 
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  FF.OLS
## BP = 16.302, df = 3, p-value = 0.0009834

H0 rejected in both models: detected heteroskedastic residuals.


ncv test for heteroskedasticity (H0:homoskedasticity, alpha level = 0.05).

ncvTest(s.i.OLS)
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 31.55482, Df = 1, p = 1.9389e-08
ncvTest(FF.OLS)
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 28.8015, Df = 1, p = 8.0189e-08

The ncv test detects heteroskedasticity in both model residuals too.


Autocorrelation of the residuals

Durbin-Watson test (H0: no autocorrelation, alpha level = 0.05).

durbinWatsonTest(s.i.OLS)

durbinWatsonTest(FF.OLS)

##    1      0.04196389      1.909055   0.682
##  Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0

The test doesnt reject H0: no autocorrelation is detected in both model residuals.


Breusch-Godfrey test (H0: no autocorrelation, alpha=0.05).

Conclusions:
- both models display heteroskedastic and not autocorrelated residuals;
- both have stationary residuals with fat tails, but normality is assumned.

At least theoretically, the regression results may be distorted due to the heteroskedasticity problem.

Conclusions


This paper explained how to use the R software to analyze the stock returns of a company. Among the packages presented, some belong to the tidyverse: its a bundle of packages which function with slighly different code syntax with respect to the R base packages.

Here, some conclusions are drown.

ARMOURs excess returns, in the period January 2016 - December 2020, display a market beta of 1.046 according to the Single-Index model and a white noise structure. The companys returns are characterized by fat tails, but this is not a surprise.
The Fama-French model suggests that ARMOUR is exposed to extra-market risk factors proxied by the HML variable.
During the COVID-19 pandemic outbreak period the data display a volatility cluster and a whopping negative return of -50.98%, followed by a slow increasing of stock prices.
